## 2. Wasted Effort — Duplicate Folder Structure

**What happened:**
At the start, a separate `nlp_engine/` folder was created and code was started there (requirements.txt, app/main.py, app/services/nlp_service.py). Several hours later, it was discovered that a fully working backend already existed inside `backend/nlp/` with M1, M2, and M3 already implemented, with complete JSON data files and unit tests.

**Why it happened:**
The project folder was not fully explored before starting to write code. The assumption was that because only 3 files were visible at the root level, no backend code existed yet.

**Impact:**
- Time spent creating the `nlp_engine/` folder and early code was completely wasted
- Two separate server structures existed for a while causing confusion
- The `nlp_engine/` folder still sits in the project unused

---

## 3. Architecture Confusion — Multiple Direction Changes

**What happened:**
Before any code was written, there were multiple rounds of back-and-forth discussions about fundamental architecture decisions:
- Should we use LLMs or not? (Changed from yes → no)
- Should the frontend use Function Calling or raw API calls? (The user did not know what Function Calling was)
- Should SpaCy be used or not? (Changed from yes → no, due to Python version)
- Which folder should the backend live in? (`nlp_engine/` vs `backend/nlp/`)

**Why it happened:**
The team was figuring things out in real-time during the hackathon. There was no pre-agreed technical design document that was locked before building.

**Impact:**
- A significant portion of time was spent in planning and discussion rather than coding
- Multiple approaches were partially started before being abandoned

---

## 4. No Unit Tests for M4

**What happened:**
When M1, M2, and M3 were discovered in `backend/nlp/`, they each had proper unit test files (`test_nlp.py`, `test_pathway.py`, `test_hospital.py`) with 15–20 test cases each covering edge cases, negation, emergency detection, and schema validation.

M4 (Cost Estimation Engine) was built from scratch without any unit test file. Testing was done only manually via the FastAPI `/docs` UI.

**Why it happened:**
M4 was built quickly under time pressure. Writing test cases was deprioritized.

**Impact:**
- If the cost calculation logic has bugs (e.g., wrong multiplier applied), they may only be discovered when the frontend team hits a wrong number
- Less confidence in the correctness of PM-JAY out-of-pocket calculations

